        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "template--16125431546025__5745a96a-89f1-43ff-b4e6-2d5a49f7d900-1682331895cf99bbfc-0"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "remove_spacing_top": true,
        "remove_spacing_bottom": true,
        "enable_newsletter_subscribe": false,
        "klaviyo_form_id": "",
        "media_position": "left",
        "media_position_mobile": "bottom",
        "media_width": "6",
        "content_position": "topLeftSticky",
        "subheading": "",
        "title": "<p><em>Sustainability Considerations</em></p>",
        "description": "<p>Laboratory grown diamonds are often perceived as a more sustainable option, however the reality is nuanced.</p><p><br/>Key considerations include:</p><ul><li><strong>Energy intensive production <br/></strong>Diamond growth requires extremely high temperatures and sustained energy input.</li><li><strong>Energy source matters<br/> </strong>A large proportion of global production occurs in regions reliant on coal powered electricity.</li><li><strong>Water usage<br/></strong> Significant water is required for cooling systems during production.</li><li><strong>Raw material inputs<br/></strong> Despite being “grown”, these diamonds still rely on mined diamond 'seeds'.<br/>For a laboratory grown diamond to be considered more sustainable, it would require:</li><li>Renewable energy sources</li><li>Transparent supply chains</li><li>Verified carbon reduction or offsetting<br/></li></ul><p>At present, <strong>industry wide transparency remains limited</strong>, making these claims difficult to fully validate.</p>",
        "colour_style": "dark",
        "button_1_text": "",
        "button_1_link": "",
        "button_style": "underline"
      }
    },
